00:03:53.059 --> 00:03:59.740
I'm so excited to be joined by our featured leader and co-host, Martin Stein, Chief Analytics

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:02.419
Officer at ConversionLogix.

00:04:02.419 --> 00:04:10.619
And I've known Martin as a customer all the way back in 2018, I believe, a colleague,

00:04:10.699 --> 00:04:12.699
and now a Hangout featured leader.

00:04:12.699 --> 00:04:16.380
So Martin, I'd love to have you introduce yourself, share a little bit about your role

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.619
today, and also something you like to do outside of work too.

00:04:19.619 --> 00:04:27.299
Hey, Rachel, and hey, Libby, hey, community, it's awesome, wonderful to be here.

00:04:27.299 --> 00:04:31.619
So yeah, it's like, I think at least 2018, maybe even a little bit early, I was probably

00:04:31.619 --> 00:04:39.040
one of the first Commercial Connect customers, if I think that might go back to 2016 or so,

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:40.339
so quite a while.

00:04:40.339 --> 00:04:47.420
So my background is I work for an agency called ConversionLogix, a tech-enabled agency

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:52.779
in the space of apartment rentals and senior living rentals.

00:04:52.779 --> 00:04:59.500
The company provides services for marketing, media services, advertisement, and of course,

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:03.660
there's a clear indication that you need data science to optimize out of that, and that's

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:05.220
what we're doing.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:09.260
So my background, I started real quick at the age of 18.

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:15.500
My first software company, studied then political science and sociology, statistics, got all

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:22.540
into SPSS, and as I was a coder, it didn't take too long to start R, and I've been using

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:29.899
R probably for, since 2008, nine, for a long, long time.

00:05:29.899 --> 00:05:35.500
And yeah, so now I'm a practitioner as well with my team here, and things that I do like

00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:41.339
is take my dog, Camuti, she's a religion rich back out here in beautiful Central Oregon

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:46.339
onto hikes, and now she's just got up, she heard her name, I guess, and if you hear some

00:05:46.339 --> 00:05:47.220
whining, that's her.

00:05:49.779 --> 00:05:52.579
Well, it's so nice to have you joining us, Martin.

00:05:52.579 --> 00:05:58.619
So I had the opportunity to get a preview into some of the solutions your team's building

00:05:58.619 --> 00:06:03.339
because I spoke with Janine on your team, but would you be able to tell us all here a little

00:06:03.339 --> 00:06:07.140
bit more about what you're focused on in this role?

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:15.019
Absolutely, so I think a classical issue in marketing and for marketing agencies is to

00:06:15.019 --> 00:06:20.700
get the right attribution for the efforts because nothing's more annoying than putting

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:27.220
marketing budgets towards a channel, let's say, paid advertising, search advertisement,

00:06:27.579 --> 00:06:35.339
and hoping that this will work out when your real channel that brings potentially a lot

00:06:35.339 --> 00:06:38.500
of the early attention is display advertisement.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:43.660
So what we set out to do is understand what is the real value of all of those marketing

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:48.339
channels and get attribution in there that's better than what the industry standard is

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:52.940
today, which is usually last touch attribution and last touch attribution models.

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:58.660
And so we developed with the help of the open source community as well.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:03.260
So there's the companies like Channel Attribution Pro, Channel Attribution who do

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:09.179
open source packages, which are fantastic, and other packages out there, a solution that

00:07:09.179 --> 00:07:16.619
allows to do probabilistic attribution, use a smock of chains on one side, Shapley, a

00:07:16.619 --> 00:07:20.100
reward model inspired by Shapley values on the other side.

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:23.140
I think those are really then leading to outcomes.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:27.619
That's the most important part that are not just like last touch driven where everything,

00:07:27.619 --> 00:07:32.299
you know, your marketing dollars all tend to go into one channel, but you get a much,

00:07:32.299 --> 00:07:36.100
much better overview about where your marketing dollars actually really work.

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:41.059
And then the next step, when you know what really works and you spend your money, you

00:07:41.059 --> 00:07:45.420
actually have a much better strategy forward and you can optimize from there and then start

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:49.339
optimizing your campaign settings and optimizing the spend and the pacing.

00:07:49.339 --> 00:07:54.619
So that's where we started with conversion logics.

00:07:54.619 --> 00:07:57.739
And this week is actually our launch week.

00:07:57.739 --> 00:08:01.500
We just bring our product to market and super proud.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:04.339
We did this in a super short amount of time.

00:08:04.339 --> 00:08:10.899
I think we started in February here and use a whole lot of R and Python, but frankly,

00:08:10.899 --> 00:08:14.540
without Connect, I don't think we would have been able to do this so fast.

00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:16.619
And so we're going to talk about technology we're using.

00:08:16.619 --> 00:08:18.140
How do we manage workflows?

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:20.420
What are the obstacles we have overcome?

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:23.260
What's the typical agency issue that you have to deal with?

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:26.500
So many learnings today that I'm actually happy to share with you.

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:27.500
Thanks, Martin.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:35.260
So I know we'll get into the use cases a little bit more later as well, but when you first

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:39.900
joined the chat today, we were talking a little bit about some of the struggles that you see

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:44.179
data scientists facing, and I thought it might be good to start off with talking a little

00:08:44.179 --> 00:08:45.419
bit about that.

00:08:45.419 --> 00:08:48.179
What are some of those daily struggles?

00:08:48.179 --> 00:08:55.820
Yeah, I think all the people who work in the data science capacity or in a data capacity,

00:08:55.820 --> 00:09:00.940
sometimes it's just like data engineers that come out of data science or the other way

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:01.940
around.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:05.979
And then you see people wearing different hats, machine learning engineers, and so on.

00:09:05.979 --> 00:09:14.020
So I think all of us that deal with data and that produce outcomes, if it's models or if

00:09:14.099 --> 00:09:17.979
it's just like ETL, more structured data, have the number one issue.

00:09:17.979 --> 00:09:24.580
I think it's about 30% who quote, who say this, I think I'm quoting here an MLOps community

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:33.059
survey from this week that I just read, about 30% have an issue with finding data when they

00:09:33.059 --> 00:09:34.059
do their work.

00:09:34.059 --> 00:09:36.940
I mean, that is a huge, huge issue.

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:43.979
And when you have your data locked up in systems, for us as data scientists, it's like, yeah,

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:45.940
let's get me some data.

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:46.940
And then I start modeling.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:52.140
But that is usually not the way when you build something that is then down the road, has

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:57.619
to run every day, has to be refreshed every day with data, where you have like data validation

00:09:57.619 --> 00:09:58.619
tools in there.

00:09:58.619 --> 00:10:00.419
We should talk about this too, because they're really key.

00:10:00.419 --> 00:10:03.739
That's something we discovered that we need data validation tools.

00:10:03.739 --> 00:10:08.419
So I think that's number one, that's the biggest struggle is really access to data.

00:10:08.419 --> 00:10:09.859
I think people know how to model.

00:10:09.859 --> 00:10:18.500
I think people know how to use tidy models or a Python environment to do that.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:21.340
So I think that's not really the big struggle.

00:10:21.340 --> 00:10:24.780
The second part is really data inconsistency.

00:10:24.780 --> 00:10:31.260
And when data is not the way you expect data to be, and then whatever you build starts

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:33.820
choking and then you have to build code around this.

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:39.380
And then you get from the 20% that you put in there to really come out with an ADA and

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:44.940
a model and something that makes sense, then you got to take care of all of that data issues.

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:50.460
So those are probably the two top issues that pretty much all of us in data science and

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:53.719
the machine learning and specifically data engineering affect.

00:10:53.719 --> 00:11:00.260
And then there are a lot of downstream issues that are, I feel like, how do we put things

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:01.419
in production?

00:11:01.419 --> 00:11:03.140
How do we make it repeatable?

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:05.820
How do we show and share our value that we create?

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:09.900
And we should talk about this too, because I think that is another big issue.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:14.780
And the third bucket, that's the last bucket I would add, is teams.

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:17.099
How do teams work with each other?

00:11:17.099 --> 00:11:19.500
And very often you see a lot of issues.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:22.419
We can dig into that as well.

00:11:22.419 --> 00:11:25.020
Sometimes I'm wondering, because I'm in those teams, is it me?

00:11:25.020 --> 00:11:28.419
Then I realized that, no, it's not just, it's everywhere.

00:11:28.419 --> 00:11:33.940
I mean, wherever you go, teams sometimes have different goals.

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:38.820
So you have a business team or you have a data team or data science team, and then might

00:11:38.820 --> 00:11:42.580
not be aligned with what is the goal that they have to do.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:46.419
Then sometimes they're not clear about who has what responsibilities.

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:49.580
Is it your responsibility to take care of data?

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:54.539
Is it your responsibility to make sure that what you put out is validated?

00:11:54.539 --> 00:12:01.299
Does a data scientist, should a data scientist go into some aspects of infrastructure, which

00:12:01.299 --> 00:12:06.020
is a real, real big issue, because who else would do it for you if you're in a small team?

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:07.700
Really big, important topic.

00:12:07.700 --> 00:12:13.539
So I think those are the three buckets here, is really getting the clear and right data,

00:12:13.539 --> 00:12:19.099
making sure that you can repeat having that same data approach for ETL, what do you do?

00:12:19.099 --> 00:12:22.780
Then modeling, I'm not talking too much about, but when you have your model done, putting

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:26.500
things into production, making that reliable.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:28.460
And last but not least, how do you work with teams?

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.380
Those to me are the three biggest issues.

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:31.380
Yeah.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:34.380
Well, thank you.

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:38.539
I realized when you were first explaining what you're working on and some of the problems

00:12:38.539 --> 00:12:46.419
you're solving for marketing and attribution, I am in marketing, but I realized a lot of

00:12:46.419 --> 00:12:49.619
us might not be from a marketing background.

00:12:49.619 --> 00:12:54.219
And so I know Libby, you had a question that you just asked, want to jump in?

00:12:54.219 --> 00:12:57.979
Yeah, you kept mentioning last touch, and I think I know what that means.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:03.659
I think it means like the credit goes to the person who had the last touch or the interaction

00:13:03.659 --> 00:13:04.659
that was the last touch.

00:13:04.659 --> 00:13:08.059
But I was wondering if you could explain a little bit about that and why that's a problem

00:13:08.059 --> 00:13:09.820
that even needs to be solved.

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:10.820
Yeah.

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:12.500
Love the question.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.619
So when people say love the question, they usually have lousy answers.

00:13:15.619 --> 00:13:18.659
I hope I have a good answer for you here.

00:13:18.659 --> 00:13:23.820
Last touch, if you think about a customer journey, so what do we do when we search for

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:24.820
something?

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:30.219
So let me give you an example out of my business background here in apartment rentals.

00:13:30.219 --> 00:13:36.059
So if you're moving from one location to another, you're looking for an apartment, usually what

00:13:36.059 --> 00:13:41.739
happens is that you potentially go on a search site or you type it into Google, or you go

00:13:41.739 --> 00:13:46.340
into something we call an internet listing service, like, you know, some that are there

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:52.179
for apartment rentals, or you have social media, you see something on TikTok.

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:57.299
What happens is there's so many different marketing channels, that's what we call a

00:13:57.299 --> 00:14:00.020
marketing channel, this is a medium.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:05.219
And when you as a user click on one of those, you know, pieces of information could also

00:14:05.219 --> 00:14:11.539
be organic, a blog post, and then as a next step, say, hey, look, I'm actually really

00:14:11.539 --> 00:14:14.340
interested in learning more about this.

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:18.859
The people who put that information out, they want to know, where did you come from?

00:14:19.419 --> 00:14:23.500
I mean, I'm sure when you go to a store and people will say to you, hey, how did you learn

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:24.500
about us?

00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:27.260
That's literally the last touch question, right?

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:30.979
So because you said, well, a friend told me, so that's the last step.

00:14:30.979 --> 00:14:35.340
But maybe you've heard about them before, before a friend or you have noticed them,

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:37.260
but you never really thought about this.

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:41.380
So in marketing, we're really interested in knowing the whole customer journey.

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:45.340
How did you become aware of the brand, of our brand?

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:47.900
Why did you come and see this?

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:49.380
Was there a specific reason?

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:51.140
So we would like to know.

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:56.419
And the reason for that is if we do not only know you're walking into a, let's say, apartment

00:14:56.419 --> 00:15:00.700
into at the front leasing desk and say, and somebody asks you and say, well, because a

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:04.900
friend told me, but you could say, hey, look, those are the five things that I learned about

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:08.419
you the last four weeks.

00:15:08.419 --> 00:15:10.739
That would be incredible, but nobody does that.

00:15:10.739 --> 00:15:12.940
So we have to make sure we can measure that.

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:19.059
And so what we do is basically take the data that we can get out of advertising systems

00:15:19.059 --> 00:15:23.739
and individual systems like your website, and then combine that data and then construct

00:15:23.739 --> 00:15:24.940
that journey.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:30.340
So then we see not only the last touch, the last person who told you or gave you the information

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:34.780
to come here, that's what we refer to usually very often as source medium, but we know the

00:15:34.780 --> 00:15:35.780
entire journey.

00:15:35.780 --> 00:15:39.380
And so why is that entire journey so important?

00:15:39.380 --> 00:15:43.500
That is because at the end of the day, that's what brought you here.

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:51.460
And between each step in this entire journey, there's a probability that we as marketers,

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:52.580
that we have affected you.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:56.140
And we want to know this because it's our marketing dollars going into that.

00:15:56.140 --> 00:15:57.380
So let's put it this way.

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:03.219
If there was a YouTube campaign and you might have seen this and you didn't click on anything

00:16:03.219 --> 00:16:05.619
at this point, but you just watched it.

00:16:05.619 --> 00:16:10.020
And then later on, you walk into that apartment building and visit, we would like to know

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:11.340
if you've seen that.

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:18.979
So that brings another real huge problem in marketing, which is first party data and third

00:16:18.979 --> 00:16:22.979
party data and data that we might have or might not have.

00:16:22.979 --> 00:16:25.700
We're dealing right now with a world that is without cookies.

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:31.780
So we get less of the data that tracks you, and we have to deal more with data that is

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:33.099
just aggregated.

00:16:33.099 --> 00:16:35.820
So what is this aggregated data that I'm talking about?

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:40.739
It's like how many clicks and impressions did a campaign have, a YouTube campaign?

00:16:40.739 --> 00:16:44.099
We don't know who clicked this potentially until they go to your website.

00:16:44.099 --> 00:16:48.260
But if you just watch it on YouTube and you don't click anything, we just know impressions

00:16:48.260 --> 00:16:49.260
and clicks.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:50.859
So that could have been influential.

00:16:50.859 --> 00:16:55.979
And so what we do as a problem, what we have to solve is bring this aggregated data together

00:16:55.979 --> 00:17:02.659
with the individual data that we have in an anonymous form from our website and then basically

00:17:02.659 --> 00:17:04.939
build an attribution model out of this.

00:17:04.939 --> 00:17:11.819
So we build the customer journey, then we use basically the unified attribution model

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:17.900
approach where we take a reward model on one side and combine this with the customer journeys

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:20.859
that come out of Markov chains and then fuse this together.

00:17:20.859 --> 00:17:22.020
That's basically how it works.

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:26.479
So to answer your question, if you understand the whole journey, you know how to spend the

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:30.979
money as a marketer wisely, and you're more efficient with your marketing spend, and you

00:17:30.979 --> 00:17:32.219
have less wasted spend.

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:35.780
That's the problem we're trying to solve here.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:37.780
Thank you.

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:41.020
That does sound like an impossible problem, because I can't imagine trying to figure out

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:45.020
how anybody heard of anything, even when you ask them, they might not tell you.

00:17:45.020 --> 00:17:47.939
Well, I see Marlene has a great question here.

00:17:47.939 --> 00:17:48.939
Marlene, did you want to hop in?

00:17:48.939 --> 00:17:49.939
Oh, good.

00:17:49.939 --> 00:17:50.939
You caught me in between bites.

00:17:50.939 --> 00:17:51.939
Good.

00:17:51.939 --> 00:17:52.939
Hi, Martin.

00:17:52.939 --> 00:17:53.939
Thanks for joining us this morning.

00:17:53.939 --> 00:17:54.939
I'm loving all your answers so far and how your mind works.

00:17:55.939 --> 00:18:01.939
I wonder if you can understand the context to this question, and then Jared had a follow-up,

00:18:01.939 --> 00:18:07.939
which, Jared, your follow-up is more external to clients, or I should say it's about external

00:18:07.939 --> 00:18:08.939
clients.

00:18:08.939 --> 00:18:09.939
Mine is about internal clients.

00:18:09.939 --> 00:18:18.939
So in the past, and even currently, what happens is I have an idea, I propose a project, I

00:18:19.939 --> 00:18:25.939
pitch it maybe to my manager, and my manager, bless him, is like, hey, I'm behind you.

00:18:25.939 --> 00:18:27.939
I want to help you pitch this project.

00:18:27.939 --> 00:18:31.939
However, I need you to help build the business case for it, right?

00:18:31.939 --> 00:18:37.939
And I can think on those terms, but I'm used to the nitty-gritty and thinking about the

00:18:37.939 --> 00:18:39.939
data problem, right, not the business problem.

00:18:39.939 --> 00:18:43.939
And so I wondered, from your experience, do you handle any of that?

00:18:44.939 --> 00:18:45.939
What's your methodology?

00:18:45.939 --> 00:18:47.939
If not, who do you hand that off to?

00:18:47.939 --> 00:18:51.939
Just kind of how is that handled in your universe, either current experience or past?

00:18:51.939 --> 00:18:53.939
I love the question, Maureen.

00:18:53.939 --> 00:19:01.939
So I think that is the question that so many of us face, where when somebody comes to us

00:19:01.939 --> 00:19:09.939
and has a clear set of problems to solve for them, and they have a clear set of goals,

00:19:09.939 --> 00:19:15.939
has a clear set of problems to solve with, and it's already vetted, and you just got

00:19:15.939 --> 00:19:16.939
to get to it.

00:19:16.939 --> 00:19:21.939
That is an easier case to deal with, because you know, okay, let me know what's the problem,

00:19:21.939 --> 00:19:24.939
where's the data, by when do you need something, right?

00:19:24.939 --> 00:19:28.939
Well, that's kind of like usually in a more simplified version.

00:19:28.939 --> 00:19:33.939
But when you have to get to your point, go out and say, hey, look, I mean, I'm discovering

00:19:33.939 --> 00:19:38.939
those issues, and I want to make a case about we have to solve something.

00:19:38.939 --> 00:19:39.939
I'll give you an example.

00:19:39.939 --> 00:19:43.939
I mean, everybody, all companies deal with a churn problem, a customer churn problem

00:19:43.939 --> 00:19:44.939
to a certain degree.

00:19:44.939 --> 00:19:50.939
You do really good work, so you might sit in your company and discover, hey, look, we're

00:19:50.939 --> 00:19:55.939
losing too many customers, and I would like to help them about, you know, how do we address

00:19:55.939 --> 00:19:56.939
this?

00:19:56.939 --> 00:19:58.939
Is it that we do something wrong?

00:19:58.939 --> 00:20:05.939
So, that's a classical situation where you, as a data scientist, as in an organization

00:20:05.939 --> 00:20:08.939
or in a team, have an idea about what to do.

00:20:08.939 --> 00:20:12.939
Classically, to me, that has been the situation throughout my career.

00:20:12.939 --> 00:20:18.939
I have been a data scientist and a chief product officer, so I always cover both areas, the

00:20:18.939 --> 00:20:23.939
problem discovery and the problem solution, and then the technical implementation with

00:20:23.939 --> 00:20:24.939
my teams and myself.

00:20:24.939 --> 00:20:29.939
So, I come out of a really, you know, of a group of people who discover those problems

00:20:29.939 --> 00:20:33.939
in great business cases and then put a solution forward.

00:20:33.939 --> 00:20:35.939
That's my daily life, basically.

00:20:35.939 --> 00:20:42.939
So, the way to do that is really get very clear about what's the impact that this problem

00:20:42.939 --> 00:20:44.939
that you want to solve has.

00:20:44.939 --> 00:20:51.939
If the impact is quantifiable and the impact is easy to understand for your stakeholders,

00:20:51.939 --> 00:20:56.939
then I think the first thing that I would do is, like, you know, kick off a little bit

00:20:56.939 --> 00:20:59.939
of a research project for you.

00:20:59.939 --> 00:21:04.939
It doesn't have to be big, about just getting your stakeholders, the audience that potentially

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:10.939
makes your business decision, if you get the time and resources to solve that issue, to

00:21:10.939 --> 00:21:12.939
get them actually understand what the problem is.

00:21:12.939 --> 00:21:18.939
So, that is the hardest part because you might go into the technical details and how to solve

00:21:18.939 --> 00:21:21.939
it, but it's not about the how at this point.

00:21:21.939 --> 00:21:26.939
You purely have to focus on why it matters and why it matters to your organization or

00:21:26.939 --> 00:21:27.939
your team.

00:21:27.939 --> 00:21:31.939
And so, that's usually very high level and you don't spend a lot of time in 20 different

00:21:31.939 --> 00:21:32.939
cases.

00:21:32.939 --> 00:21:35.939
You just bring up the one, two, three biggest problems.

00:21:35.939 --> 00:21:39.939
And then for the stakeholders, they have to make a trade-off decision.

00:21:39.939 --> 00:21:41.939
Do we do this or do we do something else?

00:21:41.939 --> 00:21:45.939
Do you understand that everything they do is a trade-off decision?

00:21:45.939 --> 00:21:47.939
You put it in the context of all the other stuff, right?

00:21:47.939 --> 00:21:48.939
So, that's what I do.

00:21:48.939 --> 00:21:50.939
If they say, hey, look, churn is good.

00:21:50.939 --> 00:21:54.939
We have like maybe keep 99, 95% of our customers.

00:21:54.939 --> 00:21:57.939
Then I say, well, maybe it's not the churn part here.

00:21:57.939 --> 00:22:01.939
Maybe we have to make sure that customer lifetime value is really the thing that we're going

00:22:01.939 --> 00:22:02.939
after.

00:22:02.939 --> 00:22:03.939
So, we keep them longer.

00:22:03.939 --> 00:22:04.939
We don't even know how long we keep them.

00:22:04.939 --> 00:22:06.939
Shouldn't we know this in the first place?

00:22:06.939 --> 00:22:09.939
So, when churn happens, then we can address this.

00:22:09.939 --> 00:22:13.939
So, that's kind of like the stuff that you have to put forward.

00:22:14.939 --> 00:22:19.939
The best method to do this is to have conversations with the business owners.

00:22:19.939 --> 00:22:20.939
That's what I do.

00:22:20.939 --> 00:22:24.939
I sit down and listen and talk to them very frequently.

00:22:24.939 --> 00:22:26.939
Try to understand what the issues are.

00:22:26.939 --> 00:22:30.939
And that's the same what we do as a marketing company with our customers.

00:22:30.939 --> 00:22:32.939
Maybe today it's not the attribution piece.

00:22:32.939 --> 00:22:35.939
Maybe today it's like they have a competitor across the street.

00:22:35.939 --> 00:22:38.939
And then we would like to understand what it is.

00:22:38.939 --> 00:22:42.939
And once we understand this and contextualize the problem, that's really the most important

00:22:42.939 --> 00:22:43.939
thing.

00:22:43.939 --> 00:22:47.939
And then help them make a trade-off decision, second most important thing.

00:22:47.939 --> 00:22:49.939
Then you have basically the first step done.

00:22:49.939 --> 00:22:51.939
And then the rest follows what you usually do.

00:22:51.939 --> 00:22:55.939
It's like do your work, get your data, do your EDA, put forward with whatever comes

00:22:55.939 --> 00:22:56.939
out of your work.

00:22:56.939 --> 00:23:01.939
And then basically do your presentation in a way that if you have a one-off research

00:23:01.939 --> 00:23:05.939
project that gives the answer to a certain problem.

00:23:05.939 --> 00:23:09.939
I hope that kind of answers your question, Marlene.

00:23:10.939 --> 00:23:11.939
Very much.

00:23:11.939 --> 00:23:13.939
There's some great nuggets of wisdom in there.

00:23:13.939 --> 00:23:15.939
So I appreciate that response.

00:23:15.939 --> 00:23:18.939
I'm going to digest that a bit because it takes me a minute.

00:23:18.939 --> 00:23:20.939
I'm coffee-free for five months.

00:23:20.939 --> 00:23:22.939
My brain is not happy.

00:23:22.939 --> 00:23:26.939
I'm going to hand it off to Jared, who had a similar question.

00:23:26.939 --> 00:23:28.939
But I think his was more like external client-facing.

00:23:28.939 --> 00:23:32.939
So Jared, if you're on, if you want to hop in, I appreciate it.

00:23:35.939 --> 00:23:37.939
Yeah, can you guys hear me okay?

00:23:37.939 --> 00:23:38.939
Yeah, there we go.

00:23:39.939 --> 00:23:42.939
Yeah, so all great points.

00:23:42.939 --> 00:23:45.939
And kind of like Marlene, I'm digesting.

00:23:45.939 --> 00:23:52.939
But I really am thinking from a standpoint of if you are forward-facing out to a client

00:23:52.939 --> 00:24:02.939
or trying to give them a pitch or a use case to secure business or really just provide

00:24:02.939 --> 00:24:08.939
that service of having to explain to them or maybe, I don't want to say dummy down,

00:24:08.939 --> 00:24:14.939
but provide a high-level idea to them in order for them to agree or for it to move forward.

00:24:14.939 --> 00:24:18.939
Can you kind of walk me through your thought process when you approach a client?

00:24:18.939 --> 00:24:21.939
I mean, I know it may be, it's going to be different for each person,

00:24:21.939 --> 00:24:25.939
but kind of the overall idea when you go into that?

00:24:25.939 --> 00:24:26.939
Oh, absolutely.

00:24:26.939 --> 00:24:28.939
Love the question, Jared.

00:24:28.939 --> 00:24:32.939
So out of my experience, I deal a lot with investors too.

00:24:32.939 --> 00:24:37.939
So I think one of the toughest pieces when you go to a venture capitalist

00:24:37.939 --> 00:24:40.939
and make a case for getting $10 million, right?

00:24:40.939 --> 00:24:42.939
That's a whole lot of money for them to spend.

00:24:42.939 --> 00:24:45.939
So your case has to be really, really, really good.

00:24:45.939 --> 00:24:48.939
So it's not just like, oh, let's have a conversation, but it goes beyond,

00:24:48.939 --> 00:24:52.939
let's say, somebody, you know, willing to put that much money into an idea.

00:24:52.939 --> 00:24:55.939
And the same thing goes, is valid for clients.

00:24:55.939 --> 00:24:58.939
When we speak with clients, I also hear conversion logics.

00:24:58.939 --> 00:25:06.939
So I think to me, it really breaks down, Jared, into three aspects that I follow.

00:25:06.939 --> 00:25:15.939
Number one is I always open my conversations with framing the situation about who we are,

00:25:15.939 --> 00:25:20.939
who I am, who the organization is, so they know where I'm coming from, right?

00:25:20.939 --> 00:25:24.939
So they know, oh, yeah, this person comes out of this direction.

00:25:24.939 --> 00:25:30.939
So everybody else you're speaking with can contextualize you and know what to ask you

00:25:30.939 --> 00:25:32.939
and make sure that you're on the same page.

00:25:32.939 --> 00:25:37.939
The second piece, and that very first, usually in an investor presentation,

00:25:37.939 --> 00:25:41.939
when you go through your startup, it's the same like with the client.

00:25:41.939 --> 00:25:45.939
It's like you present yourself, say, we are conversion logics.

00:25:45.939 --> 00:25:49.939
This is what we do, and that's what people love about us.

00:25:49.939 --> 00:25:51.939
And these are the problems we solve.

00:25:51.939 --> 00:25:53.939
So you've got to break it down.

00:25:53.939 --> 00:25:56.939
And that's the same thing in a data science environment.

00:25:56.939 --> 00:26:00.939
If you provide data science services for anyone out there, you know,

00:26:00.939 --> 00:26:06.939
it's really being very important to understand, you know, what you exactly do

00:26:06.939 --> 00:26:08.939
and what the problem is that you solve.

00:26:08.939 --> 00:26:13.939
So I think that's just like setting the stage so people know when to communicate with you

00:26:13.939 --> 00:26:15.939
about what it is.

00:26:15.939 --> 00:26:18.939
Otherwise, you might not, you know, communicate on the same level

00:26:18.939 --> 00:26:20.939
and have different expectations.

00:26:20.939 --> 00:26:23.939
So really get the expectations right is the first thing.

00:26:23.939 --> 00:26:28.939
And when we talk to clients in marketing, for us as conversion logics,

00:26:28.939 --> 00:26:34.939
typical approach is, hey, look, we are here in this industry as apartment marketers.

00:26:34.939 --> 00:26:36.939
We've been doing this for a while.

00:26:36.939 --> 00:26:39.939
And here's what, you know, the problems we solve.

00:26:39.939 --> 00:26:43.939
And then you pause here and see, ideally, you have done your homework

00:26:43.939 --> 00:26:45.939
and those problems match their homework.

00:26:45.939 --> 00:26:46.939
And then you can listen to them.

00:26:46.939 --> 00:26:51.939
Next step is give the other side a chance to weigh in.

00:26:51.939 --> 00:26:57.939
So the main approach that I would – the main way I would describe that approach

00:26:57.939 --> 00:26:59.939
is consulting or consulting.

00:26:59.939 --> 00:27:00.939
It's not selling.

00:27:00.939 --> 00:27:05.939
It's really being more – you being the doctor who listens to somebody's issue.

00:27:05.939 --> 00:27:10.939
And then you're trying to understand very good, careful listening.

00:27:10.939 --> 00:27:11.939
Let everybody come.

00:27:11.939 --> 00:27:13.939
And then you have to go to the next step.

00:27:13.939 --> 00:27:17.939
When they have shared their information, then you got to – you have to aggregate it.

00:27:17.939 --> 00:27:19.939
You have to reduce complexity.

00:27:19.939 --> 00:27:22.939
If you don't reduce complexity in that conversation,

00:27:22.939 --> 00:27:25.939
if you create more complexity, you lost it.

00:27:25.939 --> 00:27:26.939
It's as simple as that.

00:27:26.939 --> 00:27:32.939
If you just go into one area and you blow that up technically, oh, we could do this.

00:27:32.939 --> 00:27:35.939
People will not know about what this means, what you're saying.

00:27:35.939 --> 00:27:36.939
They have no idea.

00:27:36.939 --> 00:27:37.939
Some of them.

00:27:37.939 --> 00:27:38.939
Some of them do.

00:27:38.939 --> 00:27:40.939
But you got to reduce complexity.

00:27:40.939 --> 00:27:42.939
So you said what you do.

00:27:42.939 --> 00:27:44.939
You listen to what their problem is.

00:27:44.939 --> 00:27:47.939
And then you got to bring this together and say, oh, I see.

00:27:47.939 --> 00:27:53.939
You have an issue here that you – for example, you have – in our case,

00:27:53.939 --> 00:27:58.939
your apartment occupancy rates are not 95%.

00:27:58.939 --> 00:28:03.939
And for some buildings in a highly competitive environment, let's say Chicago.

00:28:03.939 --> 00:28:04.939
So we can help with that.

00:28:04.939 --> 00:28:08.939
And then we go forward and say, confirm that this is the problem.

00:28:08.939 --> 00:28:09.939
Reduce complexity.

00:28:09.939 --> 00:28:11.939
Focus on one or two things.

00:28:11.939 --> 00:28:16.939
And then you say, hey, classically, that's where really trust comes in now

00:28:16.939 --> 00:28:18.939
because somebody is listening to you.

00:28:18.939 --> 00:28:22.939
And it's really a decision theory challenge here.

00:28:22.939 --> 00:28:27.939
It's like they got to learn to understand that we talk about the right thing.

00:28:27.939 --> 00:28:30.939
Then they got to give you credit, that you have credibility.

00:28:30.939 --> 00:28:33.939
That's now after you locked in into here's the problem that we can –

00:28:33.939 --> 00:28:35.939
that you said you have and we can help you with.

00:28:35.939 --> 00:28:37.939
Now you bring credibility.

00:28:37.939 --> 00:28:39.939
Now it's about the time, not before.

00:28:39.939 --> 00:28:42.939
At this point, you say, hey, look, this is what we have done for others.

00:28:42.939 --> 00:28:45.939
And then people understand, oh, same problem.

00:28:45.939 --> 00:28:46.939
You have done this.

00:28:46.939 --> 00:28:50.939
And then at the very end, you can talk about how do we go about this.

00:28:50.939 --> 00:28:55.939
But that's usually only 10% of the conversation.

00:28:55.939 --> 00:28:58.939
And then it's, again, it's like how do we move forward.

00:28:58.939 --> 00:29:01.939
That's typically my approach too.

00:29:01.939 --> 00:29:03.939
Thank you.

00:29:03.939 --> 00:29:06.939
I'm feeling so much energy from the chat today.

00:29:06.939 --> 00:29:15.939
And I love to see this lone data scientist wolf pack forming in the chat here as well.

00:29:15.939 --> 00:29:20.939
I want to make sure I get to some of the Slido questions people have asked anonymously too.

00:29:20.939 --> 00:29:26.939
And one was can you talk about how your company handles things like A-B testing

00:29:26.939 --> 00:29:30.939
and causality, interested in tools and processes?

00:29:30.939 --> 00:29:32.939
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

00:29:32.939 --> 00:29:37.939
So I think we see a big change to, well, not a big change,

00:29:37.939 --> 00:29:42.939
but we see a change to causal analysis and causal inference and so on.

00:29:42.939 --> 00:29:46.939
And classically, we did a lot of A-B testing.

00:29:46.939 --> 00:29:49.939
Our organizations did a lot of A-B testing.

00:29:49.939 --> 00:29:55.939
And I do think that on the A-B testing side, it's a classic method.

00:29:55.939 --> 00:29:58.939
As long as you don't violate the peaking problem.

00:29:58.939 --> 00:30:00.939
We all know what we're talking about in A-B testing.

00:30:00.939 --> 00:30:02.939
You do it right.

00:30:02.939 --> 00:30:08.939
And I think for A-B testing in general, it's still a common practice.

00:30:08.939 --> 00:30:13.939
I think you need data scientists or very, very knowledgeable data analysts to get it right.

00:30:13.939 --> 00:30:20.939
I'm not a big fan of those super automated A-B testing tools where, you know,

00:30:20.939 --> 00:30:23.939
you put something forward, you look at what's happening,

00:30:23.939 --> 00:30:26.939
you peek the heck out of what's happening here.

00:30:26.939 --> 00:30:28.939
This is not the way to do it.

00:30:28.939 --> 00:30:30.939
So I think classically in that situation,

00:30:30.939 --> 00:30:36.939
what you need is somebody who understands how to go about A-B testing and do it right

00:30:36.939 --> 00:30:39.939
and then have the patients to wait until the data, the test is done,

00:30:39.939 --> 00:30:43.939
and then review the test to really see if there's any significance or not.

00:30:43.939 --> 00:30:44.939
So that's one thing.

00:30:44.939 --> 00:30:48.939
And I think that's good, and we're doing this, and I think agencies should be doing this.

00:30:48.939 --> 00:30:55.939
Causal analysis and causal inference, I feel like, is a really, really interesting approach.

00:30:55.939 --> 00:31:02.939
I personally think this allows us to do a whole lot more with understanding, you know,

00:31:02.939 --> 00:31:09.939
where without an A-B test where over time series, over a certain amount of time,

00:31:09.939 --> 00:31:11.939
things have happened.

00:31:11.939 --> 00:31:17.939
We're just right now on our side at ConversionLogix getting into causal inference

00:31:17.939 --> 00:31:19.939
and causal analysis.

00:31:19.939 --> 00:31:23.939
In my last probably two to three years, it was a mainstay.

00:31:23.939 --> 00:31:29.939
I think most agencies today should probably have a plan for how to, you know,

00:31:29.939 --> 00:31:31.939
leverage causal inference and causal analysis.

00:31:31.939 --> 00:31:32.939
You can do it in R.

00:31:32.939 --> 00:31:34.939
You can do it in Python.

00:31:34.939 --> 00:31:37.939
I think one of my favorites, I have it right here.

00:31:37.939 --> 00:31:38.939
I'm going to share this with you.

00:31:38.939 --> 00:31:40.939
I don't know if my blurry screen.

00:31:40.939 --> 00:31:45.939
One of the great books is by Martin Hoover, you know, so it's like causal analysis.

00:31:45.939 --> 00:31:46.939
You can see it here.

00:31:46.939 --> 00:31:49.939
That's one of the really, really good ones that I recommend.

00:31:49.939 --> 00:31:58.939
And Martin puts out a really good theoretical context about how to conduct causal analysis.

00:31:58.939 --> 00:32:02.939
So that is my recommended read for people who have not gone into this.

00:32:02.939 --> 00:32:08.939
And then I think, you know, the bigger conversation is really, you know,

00:32:08.939 --> 00:32:14.939
goes into Bayesian statistics and how do you leverage potentially frameworks that are

00:32:14.939 --> 00:32:19.939
on the Python side, some really good ones.

00:32:19.939 --> 00:32:23.939
I think, what is it, like PyMCS out of Berlin and Germany and so on.

00:32:23.939 --> 00:32:24.939
So I think there are other aspects.

00:32:24.939 --> 00:32:30.939
So I think that's more of a tooling part than what do you pick down the road.

00:32:30.939 --> 00:32:32.939
Thank you.

00:32:32.939 --> 00:32:35.939
Amrit, I see you had a question.

00:32:35.939 --> 00:32:40.939
Yeah, this was about you mentioning, Martin, you were mentioning about CLV,

00:32:40.939 --> 00:32:42.939
customer lifetime value.

00:32:42.939 --> 00:32:47.939
And I have recently been working on similar problems.

00:32:47.939 --> 00:32:50.939
And I've been reading a book by Peter Feder.

00:32:50.939 --> 00:32:54.939
He's a Wharton professor.

00:32:54.939 --> 00:33:01.939
And I've heard a lot about him thinking that he's known to be working on CLV problems.

00:33:01.939 --> 00:33:08.939
So I was just curious, what have some of your learnings been while like solving problems

00:33:08.939 --> 00:33:10.939
for your clients or teams?

00:33:10.939 --> 00:33:12.939
Yeah, lovely question.

00:33:12.939 --> 00:33:16.939
So yeah, Peter Feder is a Wharton professor for those.

00:33:16.939 --> 00:33:20.939
He has published a couple of really, really great books as well.

00:33:20.939 --> 00:33:28.939
He puts forward his own method and principle about what metrics to follow in an organization.

00:33:28.939 --> 00:33:30.939
And I think that's where you're coming from.

00:33:30.939 --> 00:33:38.939
So Amrit, I feel like Peter Feder is a really, really good approach.

00:33:38.939 --> 00:33:42.939
He wrote with a co-author a book about how to implement it.

00:33:42.939 --> 00:33:47.939
I don't know the name of the book anymore, but I think I do have it.

00:33:47.939 --> 00:33:53.939
And I think what you need is exactly something like what Peter Feder put forward is like

00:33:53.939 --> 00:33:59.939
a good approach that us as data scientists can implement.

00:33:59.939 --> 00:34:05.939
So he's really straightforward with what values to take, how to calculate those things,

00:34:05.939 --> 00:34:08.939
and then puts this in a context that makes sense.

00:34:08.939 --> 00:34:15.939
If you feel like other VCs out there, not that Peter Feder is a VC, but VCs out there

00:34:15.939 --> 00:34:22.939
have their own systems about how do you calculate customer lifetime value and payback periods

00:34:22.939 --> 00:34:23.939
and so on.

00:34:23.939 --> 00:34:26.939
So now we're going into a more financial modeling part, right?

00:34:26.939 --> 00:34:30.939
And I feel like really what you pick there, I think that's is like make sure they don't

00:34:30.939 --> 00:34:37.939
just go for what I would not do is like get into a book of what are good marketing metrics

00:34:37.939 --> 00:34:42.939
and then just one formula that will not really help you to tell the story because that will

00:34:42.939 --> 00:34:45.939
get you a value that is potentially without context.

00:34:45.939 --> 00:34:52.939
When you create those values or those KPIs for an organization or a team, you need to

00:34:52.939 --> 00:34:56.939
understand the context of what is that going to tell you, right?

00:34:56.939 --> 00:34:57.939
What is the next?

00:34:57.939 --> 00:34:59.939
How do we put this in context?

00:34:59.939 --> 00:35:05.939
And so custom lifetime value for those who are hearing this term for the first time,

00:35:05.939 --> 00:35:09.939
it's really about an approach to understand what's the value for your customer here in

00:35:09.939 --> 00:35:11.939
your organization that you have acquired.

00:35:11.939 --> 00:35:19.939
And that tells you what to do, how to sell, how to market, how to retain that customer

00:35:19.939 --> 00:35:24.939
and how to get new customers because there's a limited lifetime potentially for that.

00:35:24.939 --> 00:35:26.939
And what's the dollar amount behind that customer?

00:35:26.939 --> 00:35:28.939
So that's what it's really all about.

00:35:28.939 --> 00:35:32.939
And that gives you in the context of your business, you know, a better planning basis.

00:35:32.939 --> 00:35:36.939
So to me, if I would be in an organization, here's the tip that I would give you.

00:35:36.939 --> 00:35:38.939
I would sit down with my finance team.

00:35:38.939 --> 00:35:44.939
If you have a FP&A team, financial planning and analysis team, they are all over that.

00:35:44.939 --> 00:35:49.939
FP&A, if you have this in your organization, you sit down with them as a data scientist

00:35:49.939 --> 00:35:53.939
and say, you know, how do we actually get, what are your challenges?

00:35:54.939 --> 00:35:59.939
That goes back to Marlene, your question internally earlier connecting back to that.

00:35:59.939 --> 00:36:03.939
So you have that team, finance team, and they have a sub-team called FP&A,

00:36:03.939 --> 00:36:05.939
financial planning and analysis.

00:36:05.939 --> 00:36:07.939
They do CLV calculations.

00:36:07.939 --> 00:36:11.939
And you say, hey, look, I mean, I know you might do this in Excel or whatever,

00:36:11.939 --> 00:36:12.939
in Google Sheets.

00:36:12.939 --> 00:36:13.939
We can do this potentially.

00:36:13.939 --> 00:36:15.939
I can help you here.

00:36:15.939 --> 00:36:18.939
And so I think you want them to explain to you what their approach is.

00:36:18.939 --> 00:36:22.939
Do they follow a Peter Fader approach or something else?

00:36:22.939 --> 00:36:27.939
And then you can actually follow up on really the metrics, make sure you have the data

00:36:27.939 --> 00:36:28.939
and help them.

00:36:28.939 --> 00:36:34.939
And to me, help always looks like the best way is to show something of value.

00:36:34.939 --> 00:36:38.939
Classically, what I do is I put forward a shiny app that I share and connect

00:36:38.939 --> 00:36:42.939
and, you know, just model something very quickly.

00:36:42.939 --> 00:36:47.939
And usually what happens is people get excited when they see that.

00:36:47.939 --> 00:36:50.939
Yeah, that's good.

00:36:50.939 --> 00:36:57.939
I think I had a takeaway that I need to reach out to the FP&A team and my company.

00:36:57.939 --> 00:36:58.939
Exactly.

00:36:58.939 --> 00:37:01.939
Don't do it alone because you go down potentially a rabbit hole of just,

00:37:01.939 --> 00:37:03.939
like, metrics.

00:37:03.939 --> 00:37:06.939
What I'm saying is, like, there's a reality in your organization.

00:37:06.939 --> 00:37:10.939
If you have a big organization like 200 people, most likely you have somebody

00:37:10.939 --> 00:37:13.939
in finance who actually does the FP&A role.

00:37:13.939 --> 00:37:16.939
And then you talk to that person and then you say, hey, look,

00:37:16.939 --> 00:37:18.939
what's your biggest challenge?

00:37:18.939 --> 00:37:20.939
And that's basically then just listening.

00:37:20.939 --> 00:37:24.939
And then we go back to what we said earlier, kind of make sure that you can

00:37:24.939 --> 00:37:26.939
reduce complexity again.

00:37:26.939 --> 00:37:28.939
Say, ah, it's all about CLV.

00:37:28.939 --> 00:37:29.939
That's your biggest challenge.

00:37:29.939 --> 00:37:33.939
And your biggest challenge is you might not have the data or you don't know how

00:37:33.939 --> 00:37:34.939
to calculate it.

00:37:34.939 --> 00:37:37.939
And then you come in and say, look, I can help you with this.

00:37:37.939 --> 00:37:39.939
Let's do a project, kick off a test together with that.

00:37:39.939 --> 00:37:41.939
You don't have to make it really official.

00:37:41.939 --> 00:37:42.939
So that's the secret here.

00:37:42.939 --> 00:37:46.939
Don't ask sometimes for too many permissions because you might not get them.

00:37:46.939 --> 00:37:48.939
Just do this as a side project.

00:37:48.939 --> 00:37:52.939
And if you have something like Connect where we as data scientists can show

00:37:52.939 --> 00:37:56.939
value just, like, immediately, this is the best part of it because you just put

00:37:56.939 --> 00:38:01.939
something together and your job is to really then get this person excited and

00:38:01.939 --> 00:38:03.939
help them to do more with their time.

00:38:03.939 --> 00:38:09.939
So the whole company benefits from your effort and your finance person's effort

00:38:09.939 --> 00:38:11.939
as well.

00:38:12.939 --> 00:38:13.939
Thank you so much.

00:38:13.939 --> 00:38:14.939
Thank you, Martin.

00:38:14.939 --> 00:38:15.939
You're welcome.

00:38:15.939 --> 00:38:20.939
You know, we have a Slido question that is sort of in this vein of helping people

00:38:20.939 --> 00:38:23.939
spark ideas and understanding what's possible.

00:38:23.939 --> 00:38:27.939
And it says, I'm a data scientist with little experience of AI.

00:38:27.939 --> 00:38:32.939
What's the best way to get a broad understanding of AI to help spark ideas as

00:38:32.939 --> 00:38:37.939
to how I can apply it at work?

00:38:37.939 --> 00:38:41.939
Best question ever because what we're doing here is the best way to do it.

00:38:41.939 --> 00:38:43.939
Join a community.

00:38:43.939 --> 00:38:44.939
That's literally the answer.

00:38:44.939 --> 00:38:45.939
That is the answer.

00:38:45.939 --> 00:38:48.939
Honestly, I could not give you a better answer to that.

00:38:48.939 --> 00:38:51.939
I'm a member of multiple communities.

00:38:51.939 --> 00:38:57.939
I'm a member of the Machine Learning Hangout in Seattle, ML Ops community,

00:38:57.939 --> 00:39:00.939
the Data Science Hangout that Rachel started many, many years ago,

00:39:00.939 --> 00:39:02.939
which is fantastic.

00:39:02.939 --> 00:39:08.939
So to me, literally what you should be, if you have time to join those meetings,

00:39:08.939 --> 00:39:12.939
go and participate in those in communities.

00:39:12.939 --> 00:39:14.939
Go on to the Slack channels.

00:39:14.939 --> 00:39:19.939
If you have a local meetup, I mean, go to the local meetup.

00:39:19.939 --> 00:39:24.939
I mean, nothing beats meeting people, explaining what you're doing,

00:39:24.939 --> 00:39:26.939
and understanding what they're doing.

00:39:26.939 --> 00:39:29.939
So it really comes down to two things.

00:39:29.939 --> 00:39:32.939
Thing number one is that you can understand that you're not the only one

00:39:32.939 --> 00:39:35.939
dealing with an issue and everybody is learning.

00:39:35.939 --> 00:39:40.939
I mean, we're all learning, continuously learning.

00:39:40.939 --> 00:39:42.939
You're not the only one who is learning.

00:39:42.939 --> 00:39:46.939
I would bet out of the 130 people, 20 people here,

00:39:46.939 --> 00:39:50.939
there would be only a handful saying, oh, I know everything.

00:39:50.939 --> 00:39:52.939
I don't need to learn anymore.

00:39:52.939 --> 00:39:53.939
So that's why people go there.

00:39:53.939 --> 00:39:55.939
So to me, that's exactly it.

00:39:55.939 --> 00:39:57.939
Be clear about how much you know and how much you don't know.

00:39:57.939 --> 00:40:04.939
And now the bigger context is how do you approach people there?

00:40:04.939 --> 00:40:09.939
I feel like when they have a talk, then go there and then get to know

00:40:09.939 --> 00:40:13.939
some other people, ask you questions, and then they will tell you what

00:40:13.939 --> 00:40:15.939
they're doing, and then you learn a whole lot.

00:40:15.939 --> 00:40:20.939
I remember just one example when Generative AI came around,

00:40:20.939 --> 00:40:23.939
and I was in Seattle, and a ton of people said, oh,

00:40:23.939 --> 00:40:25.939
let's go to those meetups.

00:40:25.939 --> 00:40:29.939
People didn't really know what racks are and so on and so on

00:40:29.939 --> 00:40:34.939
and all this stuff, retrieving an augmented system.

00:40:34.939 --> 00:40:36.939
That's when people said, this is what I do.

00:40:36.939 --> 00:40:41.939
Some brought example applications that they had running on the machines,

00:40:41.939 --> 00:40:43.939
and then they said, here's my repository, and then you can go there

00:40:43.939 --> 00:40:45.939
and look at the code.

00:40:45.939 --> 00:40:47.939
So that's really that exchange that helps you going

00:40:47.939 --> 00:40:51.939
and helps with learning.

00:40:51.939 --> 00:40:53.939
Thank you so much.

00:40:53.939 --> 00:40:56.939
I see people are starting to share some of their local meetups

00:40:56.939 --> 00:41:00.939
in the chat as well, so I encourage you to share that there.

00:41:00.939 --> 00:41:06.939
I see, Sol, you had a question a little bit earlier about Shiny.

00:41:06.939 --> 00:41:08.939
Do you want to jump in here?

00:41:08.939 --> 00:41:12.939
Yeah, I just wasn't sure how – I haven't used Shiny in a long time,

00:41:12.939 --> 00:41:14.939
but I wasn't sure how people were sharing it.

00:41:14.939 --> 00:41:19.939
I remember when I published it, it's on my local host URL,

00:41:19.939 --> 00:41:24.939
but if I don't have Posit at this particular company,

00:41:24.939 --> 00:41:26.939
I forget how to share it independent of me.

00:41:26.939 --> 00:41:32.939
So it's like, hey, here's a tool for finance use, upload Excel, et cetera.

00:41:32.939 --> 00:41:35.939
I just don't know about the modern stack.

00:41:35.939 --> 00:41:36.939
Yeah.

00:41:36.939 --> 00:41:41.939
Now, I think that is – so I think there are a couple of solutions

00:41:41.939 --> 00:41:43.939
for that issue.

00:41:43.939 --> 00:41:48.939
Posit has a hosted environment where you can actually –

00:41:49.939 --> 00:41:50.939
I don't know if it's for free.

00:41:50.939 --> 00:41:53.939
There was a free portion there in the past,

00:41:53.939 --> 00:41:55.939
and I don't know what the URL is.

00:41:55.939 --> 00:41:58.939
Was it shinyapps.io, I think, or something like this?

00:41:58.939 --> 00:41:59.939
Probably somebody.

00:41:59.939 --> 00:42:06.939
Shinyapps.io, and now there's Connect Cloud as well.

00:42:06.939 --> 00:42:10.939
Yeah, so I think I would go hosted, Sol, first,

00:42:10.939 --> 00:42:12.939
and I would set up my own account there,

00:42:12.939 --> 00:42:17.939
and you can actually then from your ID, you can use RStudio.

00:42:17.939 --> 00:42:20.939
I don't know if Positron does it now.

00:42:20.939 --> 00:42:22.939
I haven't tested Positron on that.

00:42:22.939 --> 00:42:27.939
But in RStudio, when you publish, you can connect to any target,

00:42:27.939 --> 00:42:30.939
and the hosted service that Posit offers is such a target.

00:42:30.939 --> 00:42:33.939
That's, to me, the easiest way, and you don't need to deal with infrastructure,

00:42:33.939 --> 00:42:36.939
which is really what your whole question is all about.

00:42:36.939 --> 00:42:40.939
It's like, how do I manage infrastructure when I just want to share something?

00:42:40.939 --> 00:42:41.939
I'm not a DevOps engineer.

00:42:41.939 --> 00:42:42.939
I'm a data scientist.

00:42:42.939 --> 00:42:44.939
That's what that problem is that you're talking about.

00:42:44.939 --> 00:42:47.939
And I think, thank God you asked that question

00:42:47.939 --> 00:42:52.939
because that's our daily problem to deal with is infrastructure, infrastructure.

00:42:52.939 --> 00:42:54.939
So there are two stages to infrastructure.

00:42:54.939 --> 00:42:56.939
Let's put it this way.

00:42:56.939 --> 00:43:01.939
If you have time, if you have a DevOps engineer around you,

00:43:01.939 --> 00:43:04.939
well, you can go and look into Docker-based solutions

00:43:04.939 --> 00:43:06.939
and spin up things on that side.

00:43:06.939 --> 00:43:10.939
You know, there's definitely a way to do that,

00:43:10.939 --> 00:43:13.939
and you can host this as well on Cloud Run and Google

00:43:13.939 --> 00:43:15.939
or wherever else you want to do that.

00:43:15.939 --> 00:43:17.939
So that works.

00:43:17.939 --> 00:43:19.939
There's some limitations with that.

00:43:19.939 --> 00:43:24.939
If you do business data, you probably don't have authentication issues.

00:43:24.939 --> 00:43:29.939
You have authentication issues until you might connect something

00:43:29.939 --> 00:43:32.939
with Firebase and other servers on Google's side,

00:43:32.939 --> 00:43:35.939
which I developed for authentication people.

00:43:36.939 --> 00:43:41.939
But it takes so much time out of you, quite frankly,

00:43:41.939 --> 00:43:44.939
that you want to go and rather make the case and say,

00:43:44.939 --> 00:43:46.939
hey, team, that's what I did in my organization.

00:43:46.939 --> 00:43:48.939
Let's get Connect.

00:43:48.939 --> 00:43:56.939
And we have Connect running on GCP, and it does what it needs to do.

00:43:56.939 --> 00:44:00.939
And I feel like now you would have to make a case here.

00:44:00.939 --> 00:44:05.939
First, you go to Posit's public service and create an account,

00:44:05.939 --> 00:44:09.939
and then you have authentication, all of that stuff taken care of.

00:44:09.939 --> 00:44:10.939
You don't need to do anything.

00:44:10.939 --> 00:44:11.939
Infrastructure check.

00:44:11.939 --> 00:44:14.939
And once you grow and have shown this and people like this,

00:44:14.939 --> 00:44:18.939
you can run your own Connect environment on GCP,

00:44:18.939 --> 00:44:20.939
and it's super easy to set up.

00:44:20.939 --> 00:44:23.939
I mean, honestly, I can do it.

00:44:23.939 --> 00:44:26.939
So it's not that difficult to get all of this stuff going.

00:44:26.939 --> 00:44:28.939
So that's typically the way that I would suggest.

00:44:28.939 --> 00:44:32.939
If you don't want to go the way to use the Shiny app,

00:44:32.939 --> 00:44:34.939
then there's an easier way.

00:44:34.939 --> 00:44:40.939
You can use Quarto, and you can use interactive Quarto documents as well,

00:44:40.939 --> 00:44:44.939
which is really a very cool way to showcase something.

00:44:44.939 --> 00:44:45.939
So that runs a new machine.

00:44:45.939 --> 00:44:48.939
You don't need to host anything.

00:44:48.939 --> 00:44:53.939
And then we can also go to Shiny Live and WebR in a second.

00:44:53.939 --> 00:44:58.939
But Quarto is a really good markdown approach of creating a document,

00:44:58.939 --> 00:45:01.939
having some basic interactivity in there.

00:45:01.939 --> 00:45:03.939
And I think that's probably the easiest way now that I think.

00:45:03.939 --> 00:45:05.939
So I would do Quarto first.

00:45:05.939 --> 00:45:08.939
If you're on to developing an app with more interactivity,

00:45:08.939 --> 00:45:10.939
more app-based than a markdown,

00:45:10.939 --> 00:45:14.939
then you go to Posit and put it on their servers.

00:45:14.939 --> 00:45:17.939
And if you're really serious about that, that has business cases funded,

00:45:17.939 --> 00:45:20.939
then go and get Connect.

00:45:20.939 --> 00:45:21.939
Okay. Thank you so much.

00:45:21.939 --> 00:45:26.939
Wonderful. Thank you.

00:45:26.939 --> 00:45:27.939
Thank you.

00:45:27.939 --> 00:45:30.939
I guess while we're talking about Connect, Martin,

00:45:30.939 --> 00:45:34.939
would you be able to tell us a little bit more about one of your team's use

00:45:34.939 --> 00:45:39.939
cases and how you're sharing to Connect and maybe like what is it that

00:45:39.939 --> 00:45:44.939
that app or model is solving?

00:45:44.939 --> 00:45:45.939
Yeah, absolutely.

00:45:45.939 --> 00:45:46.939
Absolutely.

00:45:46.939 --> 00:45:50.939
So when we started this session here,

00:45:50.939 --> 00:45:53.939
I was quoting the number one issue on the data side,

00:45:53.939 --> 00:45:56.939
remove the three buckets, data, putting in production,

00:45:56.939 --> 00:46:01.939
having data consistently good, know where it is, use case number one,

00:46:01.939 --> 00:46:04.939
putting stuff into production, use case number two.

00:46:04.939 --> 00:46:06.939
And then we talk about the teams on the other side.

00:46:06.939 --> 00:46:11.939
Let's remove the teams, go to use case one, which is where's my data?

00:46:11.939 --> 00:46:16.939
Typically use case for us is using pins, pins with Connect.

00:46:16.939 --> 00:46:19.939
I think there's no better solution.

00:46:19.939 --> 00:46:20.939
Yes.

00:46:20.939 --> 00:46:24.939
There are probably more other solutions out there, but pins is great.

00:46:24.939 --> 00:46:29.939
You can have actually a repository that understands where your data sets

00:46:29.939 --> 00:46:31.939
are. It's versioned.

00:46:31.939 --> 00:46:35.939
It can be centralized on Connect as well.

00:46:35.939 --> 00:46:37.939
You can actually put in local machines as well.

00:46:37.939 --> 00:46:38.939
You only connect to pins,

00:46:38.939 --> 00:46:42.939
but that's a typical use case where how we use Connect is when we share

00:46:42.939 --> 00:46:46.939
data. You have controls over who can see it, who cannot see it.

00:46:46.939 --> 00:46:48.939
And then you have versioning that comes with it.

00:46:48.939 --> 00:46:51.939
To me reduces 30% of the first problem we talked about.

00:46:51.939 --> 00:46:54.939
It's just worth it out of the box. So good.

00:46:54.939 --> 00:47:02.939
Second use case is now we talk a little bit about something that once you

00:47:02.939 --> 00:47:07.939
did your data, you run your tidy models or whatever else,

00:47:07.939 --> 00:47:13.939
or you run your scikit-learn stuff and you have everything going and you

00:47:13.939 --> 00:47:19.939
might have a shiny app or streaming app or you name it,

00:47:19.939 --> 00:47:20.939
whatever you want to run there.

00:47:20.939 --> 00:47:24.939
It's really sharing and it's the production case.

00:47:24.939 --> 00:47:26.939
Production cases have two sides.

00:47:26.939 --> 00:47:30.939
We're going to be very clear about not everything you do is an MLOps case

00:47:30.939 --> 00:47:33.939
and you have to build an enterprise application.

00:47:33.939 --> 00:47:36.939
That's kind of like where Marlene, you were saying earlier,

00:47:36.939 --> 00:47:40.939
what's my internal audience's approach, my external audience approach.

00:47:40.939 --> 00:47:42.939
Internal to me,

00:47:42.939 --> 00:47:47.939
I feel like it's really a fantastic tool to put a quarter document forward or

00:47:47.939 --> 00:47:51.939
shiny app forward on Connect. External is a little different because when you,

00:47:51.939 --> 00:47:55.939
or if you build a tool that allows, you know,

00:47:55.939 --> 00:47:58.939
to be used in another workflow from another team,

00:47:58.939 --> 00:48:01.939
you can use Connect in that context too. We do this.

00:48:01.939 --> 00:48:03.939
We do this here at ConversionLogix.

00:48:03.939 --> 00:48:07.939
So the use case, Rachel, you asked about is we do,

00:48:07.939 --> 00:48:11.939
we build customer journeys. That has little to do with attribution.

00:48:11.939 --> 00:48:14.939
That's a whole lot of data that pulls data from BigQuery,

00:48:14.939 --> 00:48:19.939
pulls it into our systems. We can do this in single machines.

00:48:19.939 --> 00:48:23.939
We can do this in the cluster environment with Spark AR and so on.

00:48:23.939 --> 00:48:26.939
So you can do this in different ways, how you deal with a lot of data.

00:48:26.939 --> 00:48:29.939
And then actually you can crunch those numbers.

00:48:29.939 --> 00:48:34.939
Now, putting it forward to share it, you,

00:48:34.939 --> 00:48:37.939
when you run, you know, your models and test your models,

00:48:37.939 --> 00:48:41.939
there's a super great framework that's called Vetiver.

00:48:41.939 --> 00:48:46.939
That is from Julia and the R version,

00:48:46.939 --> 00:48:51.939
at least I think is Julia wrote this and the Posit team.

00:48:51.939 --> 00:48:55.939
And that is another use case where you can store Vetiver models on Connect.

00:48:55.939 --> 00:48:56.939
So that's the use case we use.

00:48:56.939 --> 00:48:59.939
So we understand what happens to the models there.

00:48:59.939 --> 00:49:02.939
So I use everything, the whole bandwidth from the very beginning,

00:49:02.939 --> 00:49:04.939
to the very end and then share things.

00:49:04.939 --> 00:49:06.939
And so those are two typical use cases.

00:49:06.939 --> 00:49:10.939
So more data science focused, more fast, Vetiver is great.

00:49:10.939 --> 00:49:13.939
Gives you a good understanding about what happens with your models.

00:49:13.939 --> 00:49:18.939
And then on the data ETL side, pins, and then running data workloads as well.

00:49:18.939 --> 00:49:20.939
I'm not talking too much about modeling, as we all know.

00:49:20.939 --> 00:49:23.939
I think we all know how modeling works and how we can use tiny models in there.

00:49:26.939 --> 00:49:27.939
Thank you.

00:49:27.939 --> 00:49:31.939
You know, we have a couple of other great Slido questions.

00:49:31.939 --> 00:49:35.939
And one is, I hope we haven't asked this before,

00:49:35.939 --> 00:49:40.939
how to measure the success of a channel and compare it to the success of a copy?

00:49:40.939 --> 00:49:43.939
Okay, cool. I love that one.

00:49:43.939 --> 00:49:49.939
So that's a really tricky question because usually it's not like the success of one channel,

00:49:49.939 --> 00:49:52.939
but the success of your campaign in marketing.

00:49:53.939 --> 00:49:58.939
So if you have a campaign that uses multiple channels, right?

00:49:58.939 --> 00:50:04.939
To me, classically what we have done as marketers, we look at what's our impression share,

00:50:04.939 --> 00:50:06.939
what's our clicks and click-through rates.

00:50:06.939 --> 00:50:10.939
And if you have some kind of measurement on conversion, you look at that.

00:50:10.939 --> 00:50:12.939
So that's the classic thing that we do, right?

00:50:12.939 --> 00:50:14.939
So we look at each channel separately.

00:50:14.939 --> 00:50:18.939
Sometimes we don't understand how they connect together.

00:50:18.939 --> 00:50:20.939
That's what we're working on here at ConversionLogix.

00:50:20.939 --> 00:50:22.939
How do they support each other?

00:50:22.939 --> 00:50:26.939
And so the first thing you would do is, like, look at your channel performance.

00:50:26.939 --> 00:50:28.939
So what you got to do is, like, do you get impressions?

00:50:28.939 --> 00:50:29.939
Do you get clicks?

00:50:29.939 --> 00:50:31.939
Do those clicks convert?

00:50:31.939 --> 00:50:35.939
So is there at least in the first step, is there a key event in Google Analytics?

00:50:35.939 --> 00:50:37.939
That's how you would do that.

00:50:37.939 --> 00:50:42.939
You'd tag this as a key event, a conversion, and then you see if that happens.

00:50:42.939 --> 00:50:46.939
So that data, you basically run across all of your channels.

00:50:46.939 --> 00:50:48.939
So now how do you do that?

00:50:48.939 --> 00:50:50.939
That's the key question.

00:50:50.939 --> 00:50:57.939
You can use platforms that aggregate that for you, like TapClicks and others.

00:50:57.939 --> 00:51:01.939
They go out and reach out to your AdWords account, to your Meta account.

00:51:01.939 --> 00:51:06.939
I mean, you name it, and they put data into their system.

00:51:06.939 --> 00:51:09.939
So there are a ton of those services out there.

00:51:09.939 --> 00:51:13.939
Me personally, I would like to have everything in BigQuery.

00:51:13.939 --> 00:51:14.939
That's where I put it.

00:51:14.939 --> 00:51:23.939
So now with GA4, Google Analytics 4, you get for free BigQuery import function.

00:51:23.939 --> 00:51:32.939
So when you go into your GA4 account, you can actually set up that up to 1 million events a month,

00:51:32.939 --> 00:51:35.939
get copied into a BigQuery account.

00:51:35.939 --> 00:51:36.939
So what is BigQuery first?

00:51:36.939 --> 00:51:41.939
BigQuery is a data warehouse in Google, so it's like a nested data structure,

00:51:41.939 --> 00:51:45.939
not just like flat, like classically what we know from CSV files, but it's nested.

00:51:45.939 --> 00:51:51.939
So it's very efficient for storing, uses SQL to query.

00:51:51.939 --> 00:51:54.939
You don't need to worry about this because we have Deployer,

00:51:54.939 --> 00:51:57.939
which can do all of that cool stuff, so we don't need to learn SQL.

00:51:57.939 --> 00:52:02.939
So the thing that we do here is literally get the data in there

00:52:02.939 --> 00:52:05.939
and then basically pull the data out and analyze.

00:52:05.939 --> 00:52:08.939
So now the question, how do I look at this?

00:52:08.939 --> 00:52:09.939
I compare, first of all.

00:52:09.939 --> 00:52:11.939
I compare all the stats across all of the channels.

00:52:11.939 --> 00:52:16.939
Once I connect Deployer to BigQuery and pull this all in and do the typical modeling that I do,

00:52:16.939 --> 00:52:21.939
it's like compare things based on impressions, clicks, click-throughs, and conversions.

00:52:21.939 --> 00:52:22.939
That's number one.

00:52:22.939 --> 00:52:24.939
You don't have to have any other software.

00:52:24.939 --> 00:52:27.939
You can do this with your tools that you have.

00:52:27.939 --> 00:52:29.939
You might want to use an aggregator to pull all of the data.

00:52:29.939 --> 00:52:33.939
You connect your accounts to that aggregator and like tactics and others,

00:52:33.939 --> 00:52:35.939
they push it in BigQuery for you automatically,

00:52:35.939 --> 00:52:41.939
and then you can actually use Google Analytics with that data and you join the data.

00:52:41.939 --> 00:52:45.939
So that is how you do this.

00:52:45.939 --> 00:52:48.939
What the metrics are, we talked about a little bit.

00:52:48.939 --> 00:52:53.939
You get to impressions, clicks, conversions, and then CTRs,

00:52:53.939 --> 00:52:56.939
and then you can put budget on top of that,

00:52:56.939 --> 00:52:59.939
and if you contextualize everything that you have achieved in the context of budget,

00:52:59.939 --> 00:53:09.939
you get a very simple method but a working method for understanding your marketing performance.

00:53:09.939 --> 00:53:10.939
Thank you, Martin.

00:53:10.939 --> 00:53:14.939
So I can't believe how fast our time is going by here.

00:53:14.939 --> 00:53:17.939
I'm going to ask you more questions.

00:53:17.939 --> 00:53:22.939
But when you were just describing how you're using Vetiver and TinyModels,

00:53:22.939 --> 00:53:25.939
I think there was a Slido question that came in,

00:53:25.939 --> 00:53:30.939
and I was actually going to ask if you could expand a little bit on this as well

00:53:30.939 --> 00:53:33.939
because all of us might not be using Vetiver yet,

00:53:33.939 --> 00:53:37.939
and I was just curious how you are using it.

00:53:37.939 --> 00:53:42.939
Yeah, so I think there are two sides to it.

00:53:42.939 --> 00:53:47.939
So Vetiver to me is really a, you know, once you build your model and you put it out,

00:53:47.939 --> 00:53:49.939
you can host it, and you have the versioning,

00:53:49.939 --> 00:53:56.939
and you get basically taken care of with Connect with Vetiver data being there and being versioned.

00:53:56.939 --> 00:54:03.939
To me, the most important part about Vetiver is, like, the known data that went into my model

00:54:03.939 --> 00:54:05.939
and how does my model react to unseen data.

00:54:05.939 --> 00:54:12.939
I mean, that's literally what you want to compare, and that's the general use cases for Vetiver.

00:54:12.939 --> 00:54:16.939
That's a classical, you can say, it's an MLOps use case.

00:54:16.939 --> 00:54:19.939
Yes, I think it's a classical MLOps use case.

00:54:19.939 --> 00:54:22.939
That is the straightforward use case.

00:54:22.939 --> 00:54:25.939
There are other ways to go about this too.

00:54:25.939 --> 00:54:30.939
There's a lot of, I mean, basically, let's remove all the products that do stuff.

00:54:30.939 --> 00:54:32.939
Let's look at what is it that you want to see.

00:54:32.939 --> 00:54:37.939
What you want to see is, like, if your model produces an inference

00:54:37.939 --> 00:54:41.939
and produces predictions with data that it hasn't seen,

00:54:41.939 --> 00:54:47.939
is it behaving correctly, or are there aspects of drift, data drift, model drift, and so on,

00:54:47.939 --> 00:54:53.939
which basically means are there things happening to data that your model was not trained for, right?

00:54:53.939 --> 00:54:57.939
And therefore, what your model does is not what you want it to do.

00:54:57.939 --> 00:54:59.939
And so you need to know when that happens.

00:54:59.939 --> 00:55:05.939
And therefore, we aggregate data that comes out of the prediction, out of the inference,

00:55:05.939 --> 00:55:12.939
and look at metrics that basically says, well, this has a different distribution now, and so on.

00:55:12.939 --> 00:55:14.939
Things are changing.

00:55:14.939 --> 00:55:18.939
Once we detect that, most likely something has changed.

00:55:18.939 --> 00:55:22.939
And for you as a data scientist, at that point, you got to go back and say,

00:55:22.939 --> 00:55:26.939
well, let's take new data and retrain the model.

00:55:26.939 --> 00:55:30.939
And really what it gets you to do is, the use case number one,

00:55:30.939 --> 00:55:36.939
make sure that the model you produce is a good model for the data it sees, because things can change.

00:55:36.939 --> 00:55:42.939
One example, I can't even remember pre-COVID time, but now I do.

00:55:42.939 --> 00:55:49.939
Pre-COVID was we collected data, and then we got into COVID in 2020,

00:55:49.939 --> 00:55:51.939
and all of a sudden the environment changed.

00:55:51.939 --> 00:55:56.939
And I can tell you, because I was doing data science machine learning at the time,

00:55:56.939 --> 00:55:59.939
most of our models failed at that point.

00:55:59.939 --> 00:56:03.939
They just didn't work anymore, because behavior completely changed.

00:56:03.939 --> 00:56:06.939
In marketing, it was really traumatic, traumatic.

00:56:06.939 --> 00:56:08.939
I mean, everything was different, right?

00:56:08.939 --> 00:56:13.939
There was no more in-person, no more marketing methods that worked for you walk into a store or something.

00:56:13.939 --> 00:56:14.939
Everything was shifting.

00:56:14.939 --> 00:56:16.939
People were not spending money whatsoever.

00:56:16.939 --> 00:56:17.939
People didn't know about it.

00:56:17.939 --> 00:56:19.939
We had to rethink everything.

00:56:19.939 --> 00:56:22.939
Here's where Vetiver comes into play.

00:56:22.939 --> 00:56:30.939
When you have your models hosted and they detect that something is, or Vetiver detects, the model doesn't detect this,

00:56:30.939 --> 00:56:35.939
the systems that ML Ops, those ML Ops systems detect that things are changing,

00:56:35.939 --> 00:56:42.939
that's for you the first hint to go back and really go to your modeling part and take the new data and compare

00:56:42.939 --> 00:56:45.939
and start understanding what is different and why things are different.

00:56:45.939 --> 00:56:48.939
And the second thing is, like, you got to think about why it's different.

00:56:48.939 --> 00:56:49.939
Did anything change?

00:56:49.939 --> 00:56:51.939
Are you reaching out to different people?

00:56:51.939 --> 00:56:56.939
Has something happened, like COVID, or other things happening?

00:56:56.939 --> 00:56:58.939
That's the number one use case for that.

00:56:58.939 --> 00:57:04.939
I know we're getting close to the top of the hour, but that is my number one use case for anything ML Ops,

00:57:04.939 --> 00:57:06.939
that you want to have an accurate model.

00:57:06.939 --> 00:57:08.939
And there's a legal side to that, too.

00:57:08.939 --> 00:57:11.939
You want to make sure your model is also compliant.

00:57:11.939 --> 00:57:17.939
If you're in a regulated market, like real estate marketing has Fair Housing Act,

00:57:17.939 --> 00:57:19.939
there are other markets with regulations.

00:57:19.939 --> 00:57:22.939
You got to make sure that your model is compliant,

00:57:22.939 --> 00:57:27.939
and those are some of the ways that you can make sure there's model compliance.

00:57:27.939 --> 00:57:29.939
Thank you.

